--[[
World chat content, faction-gated AND typed.
Each faction pool (shared / alliance / horde) has three lists you can extend freely:
  lines  = standalone one-liners            -> spoken by a single random character
  duos   = two-person back-and-forth        -> two fixed speakers alternate A / B / A / B
  groups = group discussions / list threads -> a rotating cast of 4-6 voices, one line each
  shared = broadcast to EVERYONE; alliance/horde = sent only to that faction.
Placeholders work in any line. Core: %zone% %instance% %class% %bg%.
World/flavor: %profession% %activity% %city% %race% %monster% %critter% %boss%
%consumable% %item% %rep% %mount% %spell% %rare% %pvptitle% %title% %emote%
%event% %season% %timeofday% %weather% %shop% %route% %tale% %npc% %currency%
%food% %drink% %tradegood% %companion% %enchant% %toy% %herb% %ore% %gem% %fish%.
Discouraged (player-imitation; see Tone below): %role% %difficulty% %gearscore%.
See README.md or the pools near the top of npcTalk.lua for the full list.

Tone: in-world roleplay chatter spoken by CIVILIANS, GUARDS, VENDORS, and the
occasional road-weary adventurer talking about life in Azeroth. These are NPCs,
NOT an imitation of real players. Do NOT write lines that emulate player
behaviour: no LFG/LFM, no "anyone wanna group?", no gearscore/parse talk, no
auction-house adverts, no raid logistics. Talk about the world, the weather, the
gossip, the work, the rumors -- the texture of a living city -- not about
queueing for content. Keep it grounded in the lore: no real-world references, no
out-of-character meta, no fourth-wall jokes. Humor is welcome, but it should be
the kind a tavern regular would tell, not a forum poster.
]]--

return {

  shared = {
    -- standalone one-liners (single speaker)
